ty control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caulfield, Maxwell}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:People from Belper]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStage credits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell_Caulfield"}
{"title_page": "Wild Is the Wind (song)", "text_new": "{{for|the Bon Jovi song|New Jersey (album)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}\n\"'''Wild Is the Wind'''\" is a song written by [[Dimitri Tiomkin]] and [[Ned Washington]] for the 1957 film ''[[Wild Is the Wind]]''. [[Johnny Mathis]] recorded the song for the film and released it as a single in November 1957. Mathis' version reached No. 22 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' chart]]. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Academy Award]].<ref>https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1958</ref>\n\nThe song has been recorded many times, by many performers. The best known versions are one by [[Nina Simone]] in 1966, and one by [[David Bowie]] released in 1976/1981 as a tribute to Simone.{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=278}}\n\n==Johnny Mathis==\nMathis recorded the song with a flexible sense of meter, rushing some words as if they were speech.<ref name=Perone/> At the [[30th Academy Awards]] in 1958, Mathis performed the song live.\n\n== Nina Simone ==\n[[Nina Simone]] first recorded \"Wild Is the Wind\" live in 1959, this version appearing on the album ''[[Nina Simone at Town Hall]]''. Her most famous interpretation of the song was a studio recording released on the compilation album ''[[Wild Is the Wind (album)|Wild Is the Wind]]'' (1966), made of songs recorded for two earlier album projects. Simone reworked the song with slow, sparse instrumentation, stretching the vocal delivery to express soulful, hopeless loss.<ref>https://www.npr.org/2015/07/06/419252433/first-listen-nina-revisited-a-tribute-to-nina-simone</ref><ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/859137fa-0023-11e7-96f8-3700c5664d30 How Nina Simone transformed Wild is the Wind into an enduring ballad - Financial Times (March 6, 2017)]</ref> Simone's 1966 version appeared on the trailer for the 2008 movie ''[[Revolutionary Road (film)|Revolutionary Road]].'' In November 2013 the song reached number 6 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Digital Jazz chart.<ref>https://www.billboard.com/music/nina-simone/chart-history/JDT/song/802830</ref>\n\n== David Bowie==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Wild Is the Wind\n| cover      = Bowie_WildIsTheWind.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[Station to Station]] ''and'' [[Changestwobowie]]\n| B-side     = [[Golden Years (song)|Golden Years]]\n| released   = January 23, 1976 (album)<br>November 1981 (single)\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = September \u2013 November 1975\n| studio     =[[Cherokee Studios|Cherokee]], Los Angeles\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:34 (Music video)<br>5:58 (album version)\n| label      = [[RCA Records]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Dimitri Tiomkin]]\n* [[Ned Washington]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[David Bowie]]\n* [[Harry Maslin]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Under Pressure]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = '[[Baal (EP)]]'\n| next_year  = 1982\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|VbpMpRq6DV4|\"Wild Is the Wind\"}}}}\n}}\n\n[[David Bowie]] recorded a version of \"Wild Is the Wind\" for his 1976 album ''[[Station to Station]].'' Bowie was an admirer of Simone\u2019s style, and after meeting her in [[Los Angeles]] in 1975, he was inspired to record the song for his album. Bowie later said that Simone's version \"really affected me... I recorded it as an ''hommage'' to Nina.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=278}} This was the only [[cover song]] released by Bowie during this period of his career; he wrote or co-wrote the other songs on his albums.<ref name=Perone>{{cite book |author=James E. Perone |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C6bz2BFdPawC&pg=PA54 |pages=54\u201355 |title=The Words and Music of David Bowie |publisher=Greenwood |date=2007 |isbn=9780275992453 }}</ref>\n\nBowie took special care with the contemporary rock arrangement and production of \"Wild Is the Wind\", committing to an emotional and romantic vocal performance, the words drawn out more slowly and with a greater sense of loss, following the 1966 Simone version rather than the Mathis original.<ref name=Perone/>\n\n===Promotional video===\nTo promote the 1981 compilation album ''[[Changestwobowie]]'', a [[black and white]] promotional video was made, directed by [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]]. It featured Bowie and four musicians miming to the studio recording, including [[Tony Visconti]] (double bass), [[Coco Schwab]] (guitar), [[Mel Gaynor]] (drums), and [[Andy Hamilton (pop musician)|Andy Hamilton]] (saxophone). The black backdrop and stark lighting reproduced the style of Bowie's [[Isolar \u2013 1976 Tour]].{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=734}}\n\n===1976 production credits===\n;Musicians\n* [[David Bowie]] \u2013 vocals, acoustic guitar, production\n* [[Carlos Alomar]] or [[Earl Slick]] \u2013 electric guitar\n* [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Dennis Davis]] \u2013 drums\n;Producers\n* [[Harry Maslin]]\n* [[David Bowie]]\n\n===Bowie live===\nBowie performed the song during his June 2000 [[Mini Tour (David Bowie)|Mini Tour]].  A live recording from the BBC Radio Theatre, London, on June 27, 2000, was released on a bonus disc accompanying the first release of ''[[Bowie at the Beeb]]'' in 2000.  A performance on June 23, 2000 was recorded for Channel 4's ''TFI Friday''. Bowie's performance of the song, as his opening number, at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] on June 25, 2000, was released in 2018 on ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]''.\n\nBowie also performed the song with Mike Garson on piano for the Black Ball charity concert in New York in November 2006; the concert was Bowie's final stage performance.{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=279}}\n\n==Other versions and usage==\n*[[Cat Power]] recorded a version on her 2000 album ''[[The Covers Record]]'',<ref>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA36 |page=36 |author=Colin Larkin |publisher=Omnibus |date=2011 |isbn=9780857125958}}</ref> as well as a live version for [[iTunes]] in 2006.  In 2015 her version of the song was used in the movie ''[[Into the Forest]]''. \n*[[TV on the Radio]] sampled Nina Simone's version on the song \"Say You Do\" on their self-released 2002 debut ''[[OK Calculator]].'' \n*In 2003, [[Barbra Streisand]] recorded the song for her album ''[[The Movie Album (Barbra Streisand album)|The Movie Album]]'' (2003), and filmed a music video.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |year=2011 |publisher=Titan Books |location=London |isbn=9780857682901 |edition=6th|authorlink=Nicholas Pegg|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|wild-is-the-wind}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Johnny Mathis}}\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n[[Category:1957 songs]]\n[[Category:1957 singles]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Johnny Mathis songs]]\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:Nina Simone songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Ned Washington]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Dimitri Tiomkin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by David Mallet (director)]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Bon Jovi song|New Jersey (album)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}\n\"'''Wild Is the Wind'''\" is a song written by [[Dimitri Tiomkin]] and [[Ned Washington]] for the 1957 film ''[[Wild Is the Wind]]''. [[Johnny Mathis]] recorded the song for the film and released it as a single in November 1957. Mathis' version reached No. 22 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' chart]]. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Academy Award]].<ref>https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1958</ref>\n\nThe song has been recorded many times, by many performers. The best known versions are one by [[Nina Simone]] in 1966, and one by [[David Bowie]] released in 1976/1981 as a tribute to Simone.{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=278}}\n\n==Johnny Mathis==\nMathis recorded the song with a flexible sense of meter, rushing some words as if they were speech.<ref name=Perone/> At the [[30th Academy Awards]] in 1958, Mathis performed the song live.\n\n== Nina Simone ==\n[[Nina Simone]] first recorded \"Wild Is the Wind\" live in 1959, this version appearing on the album ''[[Nina Simone at Town Hall]]''. Her most famous interpretation of the song was a studio recording released on the compilation album ''[[Wild Is the Wind (album)|Wild Is the Wind]]'' (1966), made of songs recorded for two earlier album projects. Simone reworked the song with slow, sparse instrumentation, stretching the vocal delivery to express soulful, hopeless loss.<ref>https://www.npr.org/2015/07/06/419252433/first-listen-nina-revisited-a-tribute-to-nina-simone</ref><ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/859137fa-0023-11e7-96f8-3700c5664d30 How Nina Simone transformed Wild is the Wind into an enduring ballad - Financial Times (March 6, 2017)]</ref> Simone's 1966 version appeared on the trailer for the 2008 movie ''[[Revolutionary Road (film)|Revolutionary Road]].'' In November 2013 the song reached number 6 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Digital Jazz chart.<ref>https://www.billboard.com/music/nina-simone/chart-history/JDT/song/802830</ref>\n\n== David Bowie==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Wild Is the Wind\n| cover      = Bowie_WildIsTheWind.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[Station to Station]] ''and'' [[Changestwobowie]]\n| B-side     = [[Golden Years (song)|Golden Years]]\n| released   = January 23, 1976 (album)<br>November 1981 (single)\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = September \u2013 November 1975\n| studio     =[[Cherokee Studios|Cherokee]], Los Angeles\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:34 (Music video)<br>5:58 (album version)\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]<br> BOW 10\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Dimitri Tiomkin]]\n* [[Ned Washington]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[David Bowie]]\n* [[Harry Maslin]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Under Pressure]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = '[[Baal (EP)]]'\n| next_year  = 1982\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|VbpMpRq6DV4|\"Wild Is the Wind\"}}}}\n}}\n\n[[David Bowie]] recorded a version of \"Wild Is the Wind\" for his 1976 album ''[[Station to Station]].'' Bowie was an admirer of Simone\u2019s style, and after meeting her in [[Los Angeles]] in 1975, he was inspired to record the song for his album. Bowie later said that Simone's version \"really affected me... I recorded it as an ''hommage'' to Nina.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=278}} This was the only [[cover song]] released by Bowie during this period of his career; he wrote or co-wrote the other songs on his albums.<ref name=Perone>{{cite book |author=James E. Perone |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C6bz2BFdPawC&pg=PA54 |pages=54\u201355 |title=The Words and Music of David Bowie |publisher=Greenwood |date=2007 |isbn=9780275992453 }}</ref>\n\nBowie took special care with the contemporary rock arrangement and production of \"Wild Is the Wind\", committing to an emotional and romantic vocal performance, the words drawn out more slowly and with a greater sense of loss, following the 1966 Simone version rather than the Mathis original.<ref name=Perone/>\n\n===Promotional video===\nTo promote the 1981 compilation album ''[[Changestwobowie]]'', a [[black and white]] promotional video was made, directed by [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]]. It featured Bowie and four musicians miming to the studio recording, including [[Tony Visconti]] (double bass), [[Coco Schwab]] (guitar), [[Mel Gaynor]] (drums), and [[Andy Hamilton (pop musician)|Andy Hamilton]] (saxophone). The black backdrop and stark lighting reproduced the style of Bowie's [[Isolar \u2013 1976 Tour]].{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=734}}\n\n===1976 production credits===\n;Musicians\n* [[David Bowie]] \u2013 vocals, acoustic guitar, production\n* [[Carlos Alomar]] or [[Earl Slick]] \u2013 electric guitar\n* [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Dennis Davis]] \u2013 drums\n;Producers\n* [[Harry Maslin]]\n* [[David Bowie]]\n\n===Bowie live===\nBowie performed the song during his June 2000 [[Mini Tour (David Bowie)|Mini Tour]].  A live recording from the BBC Radio Theatre, London, on June 27, 2000, was released on a bonus disc accompanying the first release of ''[[Bowie at the Beeb]]'' in 2000.  A performance on June 23, 2000 was recorded for Channel 4's ''TFI Friday''. Bowie's performance of the song, as his opening number, at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] on June 25, 2000, was released in 2018 on ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]''.\n\nBowie also performed the song with Mike Garson on piano for the Black Ball charity concert in New York in November 2006; the concert was Bowie's final stage performance.{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=279}}\n\n==Other versions and usage==\n*[[Cat Power]] recorded a version on her 2000 album ''[[The Covers Record]]'',<ref>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA36 |page=36 |author=Colin Larkin |publisher=Omnibus |date=2011 |isbn=9780857125958}}</ref> as well as a live version for [[iTunes]] in 2006.  In 2015 her version of the song was used in the movie ''[[Into the Forest]]''. \n*[[TV on the Radio]] sampled Nina Simone's version on the song \"Say You Do\" on their self-released 2002 debut ''[[OK Calculator]].'' \n*In 2003, [[Barbra Streisand]] recorded the song for her album ''[[The Movie Album (Barbra Streisand album)|The Movie Album]]'' (2003), and filmed a music video.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |year=2011 |publisher=Titan Books |location=London |isbn=9780857682901 |edition=6th|authorlink=Nicholas Pegg|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|wild-is-the-wind}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Johnny Mathis}}\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n[[Category:1957 songs]]\n[[Category:1957 singles]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Johnny Mathis songs]]\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:Nina Simone songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Ned Washington]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Dimitri Tiomkin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by David Mallet (director)]]\n", "name_user": "2601:1c2:4100:ec0:494f:a99b:31c8:61b8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wild_Is_the_Wind_(song)"}
